Romer’s charter cities

The problem:

  • Worldwide there are lots of people who don’t own land, so there is increasing immigration.

If we want equal treatment and we want democracy, the solution is difficult because enforcing borders is expensive and not particularly effective.

Romer’s charter cities

Romer’s charter cities

  • If we want free mobility: people move in with different cultures and norms, we lose either equal treatment (if people are from a society that does not value gender equality) or democracy (if people are from a non-democratic society).

  • If we want democracy: have to either restrict free mobility or restrict the ability of immigrants to vote, so we lose equal treatment.

  • If we want equal treatment: have to either restrict free mobility or have an autocratic government, so we lose democracy.

Romer’s charter cities

Solution: create new cities in the middle of unused space (i.e. the desert)

  • Lay out the streets
  • Allow people to stake claims anywhere but the street
  • Worry about services like water and sewer later (but put them under the streets like we currently do)

Total Surplus

  • Total Surplus - Total Surplus is the value to both consumers and producers of all the transactions in a market. It is the sum of producer surplus and consumer surplus.

\[TS = PS + CS.\]

Market Interventions

The government could:

  • Reallocate between consumers - redistribute goods from a consumer who bought it to a consumer who didn’t.
  • Reallocate between sellers - redistribute goods from a producers who sells to a producer who doesn’t.
  • Change the quantity traded - set a limit on the quantity sold.
  • Set a price - enforce a lower or higher price.

When Markets Work Well

  • Lots of producers and consumers (not enough sellers leads to monopoly).
  • Well defined property rights (who owns what means of production, what income, etc…).
  • Enough information about the goods being sold (uncertainty makes purchasing difficult).

When Markets Don’t Work Well

  • Externalities - If a market transaction leads to an externality (i.e. production damages others via pollution).
  • Poorly defined property rights - It’s hard to sell or buy when there’s uncertainty about ownership.
  • Monopoly or Oligopoly - When there aren’t enough sellers, monopoly producers can charge excess prices.
  • Monopsony - When there are only a few buyers, they can withold transcations to force producers to sell for low prices.
  • Thinness - If there are not many transactions, (i.e. the market is ‘thin’) then there are opportunities for arbitrage.
